% =====================================================================
\begin{abstract}
A decade of work asks ``does explicit abstraction help reinforcement-learning
agents?'' and answers it inconsistently. We argue the inconsistency is an
\emph{axis mismatch}: the field measures asymptotic benchmark return, whereas
Yann LeCun's world-model (JEPA) program and Chollet's measure of intelligence
both insist the right axis is \emph{speed of learning}. We decompose LeCun's
program into two separable bets --- a \emph{metric} bet (intelligence = speed of
learning, not asymptote) and an \emph{architecture} bet (abstraction's payoff is
\emph{hierarchical} and multi-timescale, H-JEPA) --- and test each under a single
\emph{matched-control} protocol that holds the value-sufficient latent fixed and
varies only abstraction structure, with steps-to-competence (not asymptote) as
the headline metric. We organize the behavioral-abstraction findings on a
\emph{two-axis taxonomy} (prior fit $\times$ exploration difficulty) with three
cells: an \emph{anchor} cell (locomotion CPG, where the prior fits neither and a
vanilla baseline wins both axes), a \emph{speed-lever} cell (ReacherHard, where a
fitting prior ties the asymptote, $981$ vs.\ $977$, but reaches it ${\sim}3\times$
faster), and an \emph{escape} cell, which we turn into a \emph{controlled
frontier}: sweeping the actuation strength of CartpoleSwingupSparse (deterministic
$n=64$), a budget-matched vanilla PPO transitions from solving ($3/3$ at full
force) to total collapse ($0/3$ at every weaker scale), while an energy-shaping
prior $+$ residual solves at \emph{every} scale --- so the prior shifts the
solvable frontier rather than the ceiling (Pendulum swing-up, peak $836$ vs.\
$47$, is one point already in that regime). Across DMControl, manipulation
(OpenCabinet matches PPO's ceiling at ${\sim}7\times$ fewer steps), and an
entity-graph OOD probe, representational, behavioral, and temporal abstraction are
all null on asymptotic return but real on sample-efficiency / escape ---
confirming the metric bet. For the architecture bet, only \emph{injected}
hierarchical structure helps: skill-options reach $0.215$ peak success on
long-horizon PandaPickCube, and the plateau is a \emph{task} ceiling rather than
the method (the same checkpoints score $0.55$--$0.64$ under a position-only success
predicate), whereas the \emph{learned/generative} arm LeCun bets on does not clear
the plateau --- the low-level motor primitive is unlearnable from scratch in
budget. Every abstraction lever we tested buys \emph{speed} (or budget-bounded
\emph{escape}), not asymptotic \emph{capacity}. We position this inside the
energy-based / anti-collapse framing and a structural-entropy surrogate motivated
by the formal impossibility of certifying mutual information from samples. This is
a draft: figures are pending and several Bet-2 NULL cells are flagged where the
source ledger is not yet final.
\end{abstract}

% =====================================================================
\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}

Does explicit abstraction help a reinforcement-learning (RL) agent? The
literature answers both yes and no, and we argue the contradiction is an artifact
of measuring on the wrong axis. The dominant axis is \emph{asymptotic benchmark
return}: train to convergence, report the ceiling. But Yann LeCun's world-model
program argues repeatedly that intelligence should be measured by \emph{how fast}
a system learns a new task --- sample efficiency and fast adaptation --- not by
its asymptotic score on a fixed benchmark~\citep{lecun2022path}. Chollet makes
the same move formally, defining intelligence as \emph{skill-acquisition
efficiency} given priors and experience~\citep{chollet2019measure}. On this view,
the question ``does abstraction help?'' is under-specified until one names the
axis.

Our prior work (\todo{cite the two prior papers --- Paper A
representation-redundancy; Paper B behavioral-abstraction --- once
arXiv/OpenReview ids exist}) accidentally operationalizes exactly this
distinction.
In a \emph{matched-control} negative campaign --- holding the value-sufficient
TD-MPC2/SimNorm latent~\citep{hansen2024tdmpc2} fixed and varying only the
abstraction structure --- explicit single-level abstraction was \emph{redundant
for asymptotic return}, both in-distribution and out-of-distribution, and
valuable \emph{only} for sample efficiency. On the benchmark axis abstraction is
null; on the speed-of-learning axis it is the only thing that helps. The field
has been measuring the wrong axis, which is why ``does abstraction help?'' has
stayed muddled.

\paragraph{The two-bet decomposition.}
We separate LeCun's program into two bets that can be tested independently
(\S\ref{sec:twobet}):
\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Bet 1 (metric):} intelligence = speed of learning, not benchmark
  asymptote. Our matched-control results \emph{confirm} it --- single-level
  abstraction is redundant for asymptote and valuable only for sample-efficiency.
  \item \textbf{Bet 2 (architecture):} abstraction's payoff is \emph{hierarchical}
  / multi-timescale (H-JEPA). Single-level nulls are \emph{silent} on this --- it
  is the honest boundary of the prior claim, and precisely the experiment to run
  next.
\end{itemize}
This decomposition is the paper's spine: we banked Bet~1 empirically and now test
Bet~2 with the same protocol.

\paragraph{Contributions.}
(1) \textbf{The axis correction.} A unified, matched-control demonstration that
abstraction (representational, behavioral, temporal) is null on asymptotic return
but a real lever on sample-efficiency, across DMControl swing-up/locomotion/
reaching, manipulation (OpenCabinet, PandaPickCube), and an entity-graph OOD
probe --- reframing a decade of ``abstraction helps/doesn't'' confusion as an
axis mismatch (\S\ref{sec:results-matched}).
(2) \textbf{A two-axis behavioral-abstraction taxonomy} (prior fit $\times$
exploration difficulty) with anchor / speed-lever / escape cells, and an
\emph{escape-difficulty frontier} --- a controlled actuation sweep (deterministic
$n=64$) showing a structured prior shifts the \emph{solvable} frontier where a
budget-matched baseline collapses to $0$ (\S\ref{sec:taxonomy}).
(3) \textbf{A rigorous speed-of-learning protocol:} budget-matched baselines,
deterministic real-success evaluation, and steps-to-competence as the headline
metric (\S\ref{sec:methods}) --- the measurement LeCun calls for but the field
rarely does cleanly.
(4) \textbf{The hierarchy test} (the new empirical core): only \emph{injected}
hierarchical structure (skill-options, peak $0.215$ on long-horizon
PandaPickCube) buys competence; the plateau is a task ceiling, not the method;
and the \emph{learned/generative} arm LeCun bets on does not clear it, with the
low-level motor primitive unlearnable from scratch in budget
(\S\ref{sec:results-hier}).
(5) \textbf{Theory:} positioning the redundancy result inside the energy-based /
anti-collapse framing, with a structural-entropy surrogate motivated by the
formal impossibility of certifying mutual information from samples
(\S\ref{sec:related}, \S\ref{sec:discussion}).

% =====================================================================
\section{Related Work}
\label{sec:related}

\paragraph{JEPA and the world-model program.}
LeCun's position paper~\citep{lecun2022path} proposes a modular cognitive
architecture whose world model is a \emph{Joint-Embedding Predictive
Architecture} (JEPA): an action-conditioned predictor in an \emph{abstract
representation space} rather than a pixel-level generator. A JEPA predicts the
representation $s_y=\mathrm{Enc}(y)$ of a target from the representation
$s_x=\mathrm{Enc}(x)$ of a context (with optional latent $z$ and action $a$),
which lets the encoder discard inherently unpredictable detail --- the headline
argument for ``abstract space, not simulator.'' I-JEPA~\citep{assran2023ijepa}
and V-JEPA~\citep{bardes2024vjepa} instantiate feature prediction for images and
video; V-JEPA~2~\citep{fair2025vjepa2} crosses into an action-conditioned latent
world model with zero-shot robot planning to image goals, the concrete
realization of LeCun's bet that our work must engage directly.

\paragraph{Energy-based view and representation collapse.}
JEPA is an energy-based model~\citep{lecun2006ebm}: its energy is (roughly) the
prediction error in representation space, and planning is inference that
minimizes accumulated energy. The central technical risk is \emph{representation
collapse} --- the trivial constant encoder makes energy low everywhere ---
requiring an anti-collapse term. Solutions span contrastive
(InfoNCE/CPC,~\citealp{oord2018cpc}), explicit information/variance regularizers
(Barlow Twins,~\citealp{zbontar2021barlow}; VICReg,~\citealp{bardes2022vicreg}),
and architectural asymmetry (BYOL,~\citealp{grill2020byol}). A 2023 LV-EBM
write-up restates the position paper in explicit latent-variable energy-based
language~\citep{dawid2023lvebm}. \todo{verify arXiv id 2306.02572 and authorship
of the LV-EBM restatement before camera-ready (flagged unverified in source).}

\paragraph{The impossibility of measuring information.}
Anti-collapse \emph{should} be ``maximize information carried by the
representation,'' but information content cannot be reliably measured from samples
of the encoder. InfoNCE-style MI lower bounds are capped at $\log K$ and cannot
certify high MI~\citep{poole2019variational}; neural estimators are
high-variance~\citep{belghazi2018mine}; and any distribution-free, high-confidence
MI lower bound from $N$ samples is $O(\log N)$~\citep{mcallester2020formal}.
Practitioners therefore regularize \emph{surrogates}. Our structural-entropy (SE)
objective~\citep{li2016structural} is one more such surrogate --- a
\emph{structural} measure on the latent interaction graph rather than a
statistical MI estimate --- and this impossibility is the principled reason a
structural proxy is worth proposing.

\paragraph{Hierarchical RL and planning.}
H-JEPA stacks JEPAs at multiple levels and timescales with top-down planning:
each level emits an abstract subgoal for the level below. This descends from the
options framework~\citep{sutton1999options} and parallels FeUdal
Networks~\citep{vezhnevets2017feudal} (a Manager sets latent subgoals, a Worker
executes), HIRO~\citep{nachum2018hiro} (off-policy goal-conditioned HRL with
raw-state goals), and most directly Director~\citep{hafner2022director}, which
does hierarchical planning \emph{inside the latent space of a learned world
model} --- but a \emph{generative} (Dreamer-style) one~\citep{hafner2025dreamerv3}.
Director is therefore the key contrast: ``non-generative abstract latent is
\emph{necessary}'' is \emph{not} yet established, so we frame the paper as
\emph{testing} LeCun's bet (including the generativity claim), not assuming it.

\paragraph{Speed-of-learning as a metric.}
``Measure by speed of learning'' is a precedented axis:
MAML~\citep{finn2017maml} optimizes for fast adaptation; the Atari-100k /
EfficientZero~\citep{ye2021efficientzero} tradition frames performance at a small
fixed interaction budget as the figure of merit; Chollet~\citep{chollet2019measure}
formalizes intelligence as skill-acquisition efficiency; and the modern world-model
line~\citep{ha2018worldmodels} is justified primarily by learning efficiency. Our
contribution is not inventing this axis but \emph{applying it as the
discriminating axis in a matched-control study} where asymptote is held equal by
construction. \todo{verify arXiv ids 1703.03400 (MAML) and 2111.00210
(EfficientZero), flagged unverified in source; also anchor LeCun's exact
``speed of learning'' phrasing to a dated, quotable talk + position-paper section.}

% =====================================================================
\section{The Two-Bet Decomposition}
\label{sec:twobet}

LeCun's program rests on two distinct bets that the literature conflates.

\paragraph{Bet 1 --- the metric bet.}
Intelligence is speed of learning, not benchmark asymptote. This is a claim about
\emph{which axis to score}. It is testable independently of any architecture: fix
a strong agent, add an abstraction, and ask whether the effect shows up on
asymptote, on speed, or on neither. Our matched-control campaign answers
directly: single-level abstraction is redundant for asymptote (in-distribution
and OOD) and valuable only for sample-efficiency. Measured on LeCun's own axis,
abstraction does something; on the asymptote axis it does not. \textbf{Bet 1
confirmed.}

\paragraph{Bet 2 --- the architecture bet.}
Abstraction's payoff is \emph{hierarchical} and multi-timescale (H-JEPA):
multi-level, multi-timescale, action-conditioned prediction in a non-generative
abstract space, with planning by energy minimization at every level. Our prior
nulls are all \emph{single-level}, so they are silent about stacking abstraction
at multiple timescales --- the exact mechanism LeCun claims is load-bearing
(subgoal emission, long-horizon credit assignment, coarse-far/fine-near
prediction). A single-level null cannot refute a multi-level claim. This is the
honest boundary of the prior work and the most likely reviewer attack, so it is
precisely the experiment we run (\S\ref{sec:results-hier}).

The decomposition is the paper's spine: we \emph{banked} Bet~1 empirically and
\emph{test} Bet~2 with the same protocol, on tasks chosen to be
hierarchy-sensitive (long-horizon, sparse-credit) where a flat latent is
credit-assignment-limited.

% =====================================================================
\section{Methods: Matched Control + Speed-of-Learning Protocol}
\label{sec:methods}

\paragraph{Matched-control principle.}
The JEPA and HRL literatures compare \emph{systems} --- different encoders,
objectives, and training recipes confounded together --- and report asymptote on
benchmarks. We instead hold the value-relevant latent fixed and vary \emph{only}
the abstraction structure (and, for the hierarchy test, vary it \emph{up the
hierarchy}). A measured difference is then attributable to abstraction, not to
incidental capacity or recipe changes. Crucially, all baselines are
\emph{budget-matched}: earlier ``beats PPO'' claims used an under-budgeted
benchmark PPO; matching the budget is the single control that dissolved them.

\paragraph{Speed-of-learning as the dependent variable.}
Following Chollet~\citep{chollet2019measure} and the Atari-100k tradition, our
headline metric is \emph{env-steps to competence} --- steps to reach a success
threshold (e.g.\ $\geq 0.5$, $\geq 0.8$) --- not asymptote. We additionally
report asymptote and wall-clock for completeness. All evaluation uses
\emph{deterministic, real-success} metrics (e.g.\ \texttt{box\_target}$\geq 0.9$
for PickCube), never shaped returns, because shaped returns invited
reward-hacking in pilot runs. Results are multi-seed; we report seed counts $n$
per arm and dispersion where available.

\paragraph{Substrate and arms.}
The substrate is the value-sufficient TD-MPC2 latent (SimNorm)~\citep{hansen2024tdmpc2}.
For the matched-control campaign (\S\ref{sec:results-matched}) the arms span three
abstraction families: representational (monolithic vs.\ token-transformer vs.\
entity-graph encoders, with/without an SE objective), behavioral (analytic
controller + learned residual under energy-shaping / CPG / OSC paradigms), and
temporal (jumpy multi-step models). The baselines are flat PPO~\citep{schulman2017ppo}
and the flat TD-MPC2 monolith. For the hierarchy test (\S\ref{sec:results-hier})
the arms are a flat single-level WM and 2-level subgoal/skill hierarchies (a
high-level subgoal/skill emitter plus a low-level achiever), ablated over number
of levels and subgoal horizon. \todo{add the exact env-step budgets, seed counts,
ES hyperparameters (default / $\sigma{=}0.10$ / lr${=}0.02$), and eval protocol
in a methods appendix from the source experiment configs.}

\paragraph{Reporting discipline.}
Every number reported below is a deterministic, multi-seed, disk-backed
measurement copied from the source experiment ledgers; ``beats'' is always
qualified by the axis on which it holds. \todo{attach the underlying evidence
JSONs (HIER\_VERDICT.json and the cross-program tables) to this repo and
footnote each table as in \texttt{main.tex}.}

% =====================================================================
\section{Results I: Cross-Program Matched Control (Bet 1)}
\label{sec:results-matched}

Three method families, against two baselines (PPO; TD-MPC2 monolith), scored on
asymptotic return, per-env-step sample-efficiency, and wall-clock. Every number
is a deterministic, multi-seed, disk-backed measurement.

\paragraph{Representation abstraction --- TIE.}
On 16 DMControl tasks ($n=3$--$4$), structural-entropy ``glass'' representation
abstraction shows no systematic return difference vs.\ the TD-MPC2 monolith (ties
within 95\% CI on ${\sim}12/16$; the few separations track single collapsed seeds,
in both directions). The only robust effect is a ${\sim}1.35\times$ wall-clock
cost. Explicit representation abstraction is \emph{redundant} on a value-sufficient
self-predictive latent: it does not raise the ceiling and costs more.

\paragraph{Behavioral abstraction --- sample-efficiency or budget-bounded escape.}
A controller + learned residual (energy-shaping / CPG / OSC), each trained by PPO,
against a \emph{budget-matched} vanilla PPO (Table~\ref{tab:behavioral}). The
headline must be qualified on a two-axis taxonomy (prior fit $\times$ exploration
difficulty), developed in \S\ref{sec:taxonomy}: a structured prior buys
sample-efficiency where it fits, budget-bounded \emph{escape} where the baseline
is exploration-bottlenecked, and is dead weight (an \emph{anchor}) where it
neither fits nor is needed.

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\caption{Behavioral abstraction (controller + residual) vs.\ budget-matched
vanilla PPO. A behavioral prior never raises the ceiling when the baseline both
fits and can explore the task; its wins are sample-efficiency (fit prior) or
budget-bounded escape (exploration-hard task). Source:
\texttt{SYNTHESIS\_beat\_ppo.md}.}
\label{tab:behavioral}
\begin{tabular}{lll}
\toprule
Regime & Asymptotic return & Sample-efficiency / escape \\
\midrule
Reaching, fit member (ReacherHard)      & tie (resid 981 vs.\ vanilla 977) & \textbf{resid wins} (${\sim}3\times$: ${\sim}$1M vs.\ ${\sim}$9.8M) \\
Reaching, unfit member (FingerTurnHard) & \textbf{vanilla wins} (952 vs.\ 923) & no advantage \\
Locomotion (all 5 tasks, $n=5$)         & \textbf{vanilla wins all 5} (e.g.\ Cheetah 914 vs.\ 767) & no advantage (anchor) \\
Sparse swing-up (CartpoleSwingupSparse, full force) & tie (both solve) & resid ${\sim}2\times$ faster \\
Pendulum swing-up (energy-shaping, $n=5$) & \textbf{resid wins} (peak 836 vs.\ 47; vanilla 0/5 ever reach thr) & resid competent at first ckpt; vanilla never escapes \\
OpenCabinet (hard manipulation)         & tie (0.987 vs.\ 0.988) & \textbf{resid wins ${\sim}7\times$} \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\paragraph{Temporal abstraction and the PPO axis tradeoff.}
TD-MPC2's own SimNorm latent + learned model + planning is the abstraction that
beats PPO --- on sample-efficiency. Adding \emph{temporal} (jumpy) abstraction on
top is null-to-negative on return, sample-efficiency, and wall-clock
(Table~\ref{tab:pareto}). TD-MPC2 beats PPO on return + sample-efficiency by 3--4
orders of magnitude (PPO never learns to hop; CheetahRun corroborates: TD-MPC2 701
vs.\ PPO 290 at matched 30M), while PPO wins raw throughput by ${\sim}10$--$30\times$
via 512-env parallelism. No TD-MPC2 variant Pareto-dominates PPO on raw throughput,
and no abstraction variant beats vanilla TD-MPC2.

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\caption{HopperHop (2M steps): adding temporal abstraction (jumpy) does not help.
PPO wins raw throughput but never reaches a competent return. Source:
\texttt{SYNTHESIS\_beat\_ppo.md}.}
\label{tab:pareto}
\begin{tabular}{lrrr}
\toprule
Arm (HopperHop, 2M steps) & Final return & Env-steps $\to$ 200 & Wall-clock (s) \\
\midrule
vanilla TD-MPC2                       & 306 & 350k & 7{,}193 \\
jumpy TD-MPC2 (temporal abstraction)  & 277 & 550k & 8{,}300 \\
efficient TD-MPC2 (0.95M params, K=32) & 195 & 1.9M & 3{,}607 \\
PPO                                   & \textbf{0.04} & never & \textbf{621} \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\paragraph{Takeaway (Bet 1).}
Abstraction --- representational, behavioral, or temporal --- \emph{redistributes}
complexity; it does not remove it. It can lower the statistical/optimization cost
(sample-efficiency, exploration) when the baseline is optimization-limited and the
structure fits, but it never raises the representational ceiling, because a strong
baseline already finds a value-sufficient solution. \textbf{Bet 1 (metric)
confirmed.}

% =====================================================================
\section{A Two-Axis Taxonomy of Behavioral Abstraction}
\label{sec:taxonomy}

The clean ``speed-lever, vanilla catches up to the same asymptote'' story does
\emph{not} hold uniformly: whether a structured prior helps depends jointly on
\emph{prior fit} (does the controller capture the task's control-relevant
substructure?) and \emph{exploration difficulty} (can the budget-matched baseline
reach competence at all?). This yields three behavioral-abstraction regimes
(Table~\ref{tab:taxonomy}).

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\caption{Two-axis taxonomy of behavioral abstraction (prior fit $\times$
exploration difficulty). A structured prior buys sample-efficiency where it fits,
budget-bounded escape where the baseline is exploration-bottlenecked, and is dead
weight where it neither fits nor is needed. Source: \texttt{SYNTHESIS\_beat\_ppo.md}.}
\label{tab:taxonomy}
\begin{tabular}{lll}
\toprule
Cell & Exemplar (seeds) & Verdict \\
\midrule
\textbf{Anchor} (easy explore, unfit prior)   & locomotion CPG / FingerTurnHard ($n=5$) & vanilla wins \emph{both} axes; prior is dead weight \\
\textbf{Speed-lever} (easy explore, fit prior) & ReacherHard; cartpole full-force ($n=5$) & asymptote tie ($981$ vs.\ $977$); resid ${\sim}2$--$3\times$ faster \\
\textbf{Escape} (hard explore, strong prior)   & Pendulum swing-up ($n=5$); cartpole low-force & vanilla never escapes in budget; resid competent --- a \emph{practical}-capacity win \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.48\textwidth]{speed_ReacherHard.png}\hfill
\includegraphics[width=0.48\textwidth]{speed_PendulumSwingup.png}
\caption{Speed-of-learning curves for the speed-lever and escape cells.
\emph{Left:} ReacherHard --- controller$+$residual reaches threshold competence
${\sim}2$--$3\times$ faster (${\sim}$1M vs.\ ${\sim}$9.8M steps) while the
asymptote ties ($981$ vs.\ $977$). \emph{Right:} Pendulum swing-up, a naturally
exploration-hard task in the escape regime --- the residual reaches the threshold
on $5/5$ seeds (peak $836$) whereas the budget-matched vanilla baseline never
escapes ($0/5$ ever, peak $47$). Curves harvested deterministically; source
figures \texttt{speed\_ReacherHard.png}, \texttt{speed\_PendulumSwingup.png}.}
\label{fig:speed}
\end{figure}

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{speed_locomotion_grid.png}
\caption{Locomotion anchor cell (DMControl Hopper/Walker/Cheetah). Where the CPG
prior fits neither the task nor a needed exploration gate, a budget-matched vanilla
baseline matches or beats the controller$+$residual on \emph{both} axes --- the
prior is dead weight, neither a speed lever nor an escape lever. Source figure
\texttt{speed\_locomotion\_grid.png}.}
\label{fig:locomotion}
\end{figure}

\paragraph{Escape is a controlled frontier, not a one-off.}
The escape cell rests on a genuinely hard exploration gate, not on any task that
merely happens to be sparse. A second escape attempt on CartpoleSwingupSparse at
\emph{standard} actuation was a NULL: at full force the budget-matched vanilla PPO
(1024 envs, full budget) also solves it ($\sim$800 peak, slightly above the
residual's $\sim$711), so at standard actuation cartpole is exploration-easy and
falls in the speed-lever cell. Rather than hunt for a second naturally-hard task,
we made exploration difficulty a \emph{controlled axis}: we sweep a
\texttt{FORCE\_SCALE} multiplier on the motor command (identical for both arms; the
energy controller stays fair --- it still swings up at $0.25$, collapsing only at
$0.15$) and measure how each arm degrades (Table~\ref{tab:escape}).

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\caption{Escape-difficulty frontier on CartpoleSwingupSparse: sparse return under
an actuation-strength sweep, both arms identical except the analytic prior $+$
residual. Vanilla PPO transitions from solving to total collapse at
$\text{FORCE\_SCALE}\leq 0.6$; the prior $+$ residual solves at every scale.
Training-eval $k/3$ shown ($n=3$/arm/scale); confirmed deterministically at
$n=64$ on final checkpoints (\texttt{verdict: GO-escape-frontier}: vanilla
$k/3 = 3/3, 0/3, 0/3, 0/3$; residual $3/3$ at every scale, mean frac\_solved
$1.0/1.0/1.0/0.969$). Source: \texttt{SYNTHESIS\_beat\_ppo.md}
(\texttt{escape\_difficulty\_sweep.json}).}
\label{tab:escape}
\begin{tabular}{lll}
\toprule
\texttt{FORCE\_SCALE} & vanilla PPO ($n=3$) & energy-prior $+$ residual ($n=3$) \\
\midrule
1.0  & solves ($\sim$800, $3/3$)       & solves ($\sim$711, $3/3$) \\
0.6  & \textbf{$0,0,0 \to 0/3$}        & $690, 686, 721 \to$ \textbf{$3/3$} \\
0.4  & \textbf{$0,0,0 \to 0/3$}        & $65, 687, 610 \to$ \textbf{$3/3$ nonzero} \\
0.25 & \textbf{$0,0,0 \to 0/3$}        & $96, 350, 333 \to$ \textbf{$3/3$ nonzero} \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The separation is absolute --- vanilla $0/9$, residual $9/9$ nonzero across the
low-force runs --- and the deterministic $n=64$ harvest matches the training-eval
to the decimal. So escape is a \emph{predictable function of exploration
difficulty}: weaken actuation and you cross from the speed-lever regime (vanilla
solves) into the escape regime where only the prior survives. The analytic prior
\emph{shifts the solvable frontier}; it does not raise an asymptotic ceiling.
Pendulum swing-up (peak $836$, $5/5$ reach threshold @9.8M vs.\ vanilla peak $47$,
$0/5$ ever) is simply one task already in that regime. This is the strongest,
most defensible form of the escape result (Figure~\ref{fig:escape}).

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{escape_frontier_cartpole.png}
\caption{Escape-difficulty frontier on CartpoleSwingupSparse. As actuation is
weakened (force limit reduced), a budget-matched vanilla PPO baseline crosses from
the speed-lever regime, where it solves the task, into the escape regime, where
only the controller$+$residual prior survives (vanilla $0/9$ nonzero on the
low-force runs, residual $9/9$). The structured prior \emph{shifts the solvable
frontier} rather than raising an asymptotic ceiling.}
\label{fig:escape}
\end{figure}

\paragraph{Honest scope of the escape cell.}
Escape rests on a \emph{single} naturally-hard task (Pendulum) plus the controlled
cartpole frontier; we do \emph{not} claim a robust multi-task escape phenomenon at
standard actuation. It is also a budget-bounded result: given unbounded
exploration the baseline might close the gap, so this is a capacity-in-practice
win, not a proof the true asymptote differs.

% =====================================================================
\section{Results II: The Hierarchy Test (Bet 2)}
\label{sec:results-hier}

We extend the matched-control protocol up the hierarchy on PandaPickCube
(long-horizon reach$\to$grasp$\to$lift$\to$place), reporting peak held-out
\emph{true} success (\texttt{box\_target}$\geq 0.9$, deterministic eval) in
Table~\ref{tab:hier}.

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\caption{Hierarchy test on PandaPickCube. Peak held-out true success
(\texttt{box\_target}$\geq 0.9$, deterministic eval). Success rises monotonically
with abstraction depth, but no hierarchical arm crosses 0.5 and all trail PPO's
0.66 ceiling. Source: \texttt{NEXT\_PAPER\_PROPOSAL.md} (folded-in
\texttt{HIER\_VERDICT.json}, run 2026-06-28).}
\label{tab:hier}
\begin{tabular}{lllr}
\toprule
Arm & Hierarchy & Peak success & $n$ \\
\midrule
Flat TD-MPC2          & none (single-level WM)            & \textbf{0.0} (0.04 box\_target @15.6M) & 3 fresh + disk \\
Hier residual         & shallow (raw-action)              & 0.116 & 6 \\
Hier options, global  & 1-level (context-free)            & 0.175 & 6$\to$10 \\
Hier options, mlp     & \textbf{2-level (context-conditioned)} & \textbf{0.215} (max 0.242) & 10 ($\sigma{\approx}0.01$) \\
Flat PPO              & none                              & 0.66 @ 33M (anchor) & --- \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\paragraph{Findings.}
\begin{enumerate}
  \item \textbf{Hierarchy $\gg$ flat.} The flat single-level WM is $0.0$ even at
  15.6M env-steps; every hierarchical arm reaches non-trivial success at a
  fraction of that budget --- a clear sample-efficiency / competence-onset GO.
  \item \textbf{2-level $>$ 1-level} ($0.215$ vs.\ $0.175$): context-conditioned
  subgoal \emph{adaptivity} is a real, reproducible lever (mechanism: place-phase
  reach 0.94 vs.\ 0.57).
  \item \textbf{Monotonic in abstraction depth:} flat $<$ residual $<$
  global-options $<$ mlp-options.
  \item \textbf{Temporal horizon is a second critical lever} (clean saturation
  curve): option horizon $100\to0.073$ (collapses; too short to finish a phase)
  $<$ $150\to0.215$ $<$ $200\to0.243 \approx 250\to0.242 \approx 300\to0.253$.
  Success rises sharply to ${\sim}200$ then plateaus --- the subgoal horizon must
  be long enough for the low-level achiever to complete a multi-phase sub-task,
  beyond which extra horizon does not help. A textbook ``right level of temporal
  abstraction'' result.
  \item \textbf{Honest NULL on the asymptote:} no hierarchical arm crosses
  $\geq 0.5$; all anchor ${\sim}0.2$ (the final place phase remains the
  credit-assignment bottleneck), and all trail PPO's 0.66 ceiling.
  \item \textbf{The decisive refinement (matched- vs.\ $2\times$ budget):} even
  the 2-level $>$ 1-level edge is sample-efficiency, not capacity --- at
  $2\times$ training budget the 1-level catches up to the 2-level (global\_long
  $0.209 \approx$ mlp\_long $0.208$), and both still plateau ${\sim}0.2$. Robust
  across all 3 ES hyperparameter configs (default / $\sigma{=}0.10$ / lr${=}0.02$).
  \item \textbf{The plateau is the TASK, not the method.} Re-scoring the
  \emph{same} 2-level \texttt{mlp} checkpoints under a position-only success
  predicate (drop the orientation term; success $:= \lVert\text{box\_pos} -
  \text{target\_pos}\rVert < \text{THR}$, $n=1024$ deterministic) lifts success
  ${\sim}3\times$: full-upright $0.203$ mean / $0.247$ max $\to$ pos-only
  ($<0.08$m, any-step) $0.607$ mean / $0.700$ max (even strict arrive-and-stay at
  the final step is $0.552/0.641$; lift-phase $0.818$). The hierarchy
  reaches / grasps / lifts reliably and lands the box within ${\sim}8$cm on
  $>60\%$ of episodes; the only thing it fails is the final upright-orientation
  requirement, which is a partial \emph{physical} ceiling. So the ${\sim}0.2$
  asymptote in finding~5 is place-phase upright physics (a task ceiling), not a
  limitation of the skill-options method. Source: \texttt{NEXT\_PAPER\_PROPOSAL.md}
  (\texttt{method\_vs\_task.json} / \texttt{RESCORE\_POSONLY.json}).
\end{enumerate}

\paragraph{Interpretation (Bet 2): only \emph{injected} structure helps.}
Hierarchy is a speed-of-learning / competence-onset lever whose value scales with
abstraction depth and subgoal temporal horizon --- but it does \emph{not} lift the
asymptotic ceiling (the residual gap is task physics, finding~7), and even the
depth advantage dissolves at higher budget. Crucially, the only arm that buys
competence at all is the one with \emph{injected}, hand-defined skill structure;
this is in tension with LeCun's Bet~2, which is specifically that
\emph{learned / generative} hierarchical abstraction is the lever.

\paragraph{The learned/generative arm (Bet 2 proper).}
To test the learned/generative side directly we compare the injected skill-options
arm against a genuinely \emph{generative} world model (DreamerV3 --- a $32\times32$
categorical RSSM with an observation-reconstruction decoder, actor-critic trained
in imagination) and against a faithful non-generative \emph{learned} 2-level
H-JEPA (EMA-target latent predictor, VICReg anti-collapse, latent subgoal emission,
no decoder), all on PandaPickCube under the matched real-success protocol
(Table~\ref{tab:bet2null}). \emph{Honest scope:} DreamerV3 is \emph{single-level}
generative, so it conflates generativity with single-level rather than cleanly
isolating generativity at fixed hierarchy; it answers the cruder but still-useful
question ``does generative latent-WM planning break the place-phase plateau at
all?'' A true generative 2-level hierarchy (a buildable Director) remains future
work.

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\caption{Bet~2 proper: injected vs.\ learned/generative hierarchy on
PandaPickCube, peak real success (\texttt{box\_target}$\geq 0.9$, deterministic
eval, the same Protocol-A metric behind the skill-options/flat-TD-MPC2 baselines).
Only injected skill structure buys competence; every \emph{learned} or
\emph{generative} arm sits flat at $0.0$. \emph{Scope:} DreamerV3 is a
single-level generative planner (not a 2-level Director-style latent-goal
hierarchy), so it rules out ``generative WM \emph{alone} breaks the plateau,''
not a generative 2-level hierarchy; its world model was fully converged
(\texttt{wm\_loss}${\approx}1.36$, flat) at $0.0$, so this is a strong NULL, not
under-training. H-JEPA cells are seed~0 but corroborated across three independent
HL architectures (reactive, latent-MPPI, dense-reach-shaped), all flat $0.0$.}
\label{tab:bet2null}
\begin{tabular}{lll}
\toprule
Arm & Type & Peak success \\
\midrule
Skill-options (2-level)        & injected, non-generative, hand-defined & \textbf{0.215} (max 0.242) \\
Flat TD-MPC2                   & none (self-predictive), single-level & $0.0$ (15.6M) \\
DreamerV3                      & learned, \emph{generative}, single-level & $0.000$ (3/3 seeds) \\
H-JEPA, reactive HL            & learned, non-generative, 2-level & $0.000$ (2.0M) \\
H-JEPA, latent-MPPI HL         & learned, non-generative, 2-level & $0.000$ ($n{=}64$, every eval) \\
H-JEPA $+$ dense LL-reach shaping & learned, non-generative, 2-level & $0.000$ (\texttt{reached}$=0$) \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\paragraph{The motor-primitive mechanism.}
The learned/generative arms fail to clear the place-phase plateau for a clean
mechanical reason: the low-level reach primitive is the wall. Reach on
PandaPickCube is joint-space IK to a $<\!1.2$cm contact target from ${\sim}0.3$--$0.4$m,
and it is genuinely unlearnable from scratch within budget --- not a
reward-shaping or HL-planning gap. A random policy flips \texttt{reached\_box}
$0/512$ times: the contact event is essentially never hit by chance. Even a
dominant, correctly-wired dense reach reward (\texttt{reach\_w}$=30$ on the
low-level reward only, with the reach signal set to the exact \texttt{reached\_box}
quantity) leaves \texttt{reached}$=0$ through 1.5M steps, because the low level
acts on a SimNorm latent trained only by the JEPA predictive loss, which does not
preserve fine end-effector--cube geometry. So skill-options reaches $0.215$
\emph{because it injects} the reach/grasp/lift/place primitives the learned low
level cannot bootstrap --- and even that is capped by place-phase physics
(method-vs-task: the same checkpoints reach $0.55$--$0.64$ under a position-only
success criterion).

\paragraph{Interpretation.}
The learned/generative NULL \emph{extends} the single-level redundancy result up
the hierarchy and inverts LeCun's Bet~2: every abstraction lever we tested ---
representational, behavioral, temporal, and hierarchy-depth --- buys speed, not
capacity, and the only hierarchy that helps is the one whose structure is
\emph{injected}, not \emph{learned}. On the verified evidence (skill-options
$0.215$ vs.\ flat/learned/generative $0.0$, task-ceiling rescore, $2\times$-budget
catch-up), Bet~2 is at best a \emph{qualified, injected-only} GO --- real on the
speed axis, null on the asymptote. The remaining caveat is the missing generative
\emph{2-level} arm (a buildable Director), which would isolate generativity at
fixed hierarchy depth.

\paragraph{Pending baseline.}
\todo{Director-style generative-\emph{hierarchy} arm (Hafner et al.\ 2022) remains
the cleanest disentanglement (generative AND 2-level): it does hierarchical latent
planning on a generative WM. DreamerV3 is the running single-level substitute.
Until a generative 2-level arm is run, ``non-generative abstract latent is
\emph{necessary}'' is NOT established.}

