% =====================================================================
\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:discussion}

\paragraph{Every abstraction lever is speed (or escape), not capacity.}
Across the full ladder --- representational, behavioral, temporal, and
hierarchy-depth --- abstraction lowers the \emph{statistical / optimization} cost
of reaching a ceiling that a strong flat baseline also reaches; it does not raise
that ceiling. The one regime where a prior wins on a \emph{capacity}-like axis is
\emph{escape} (\S\ref{sec:taxonomy}): when the budget-matched baseline is
exploration-bottlenecked and never reaches competence at all, the prior's win is a
budget-bounded capacity-in-practice win, not a proof the true asymptote differs.
This is the unifying claim, now established across abstraction \emph{types} (Bet 1)
and \emph{up the hierarchy} (Bet 2). It reframes ``does abstraction help?'' as
axis-dependent: yes on speed-of-learning and on escaping exploration gates, no on
asymptote.

\paragraph{Why the information term is often already satisfied.}
A value-sufficient SimNorm latent already satisfies the information / anti-collapse
objective that a JEPA must enforce, which is \emph{why} an added SE/abstraction
term is redundant --- a worked instance of ``when is the information term already
satisfied?'' The structural-entropy surrogate is motivated, not as a solution to
the McAllester--Stratos impossibility, but as a tractable, assumption-light
\emph{structural} proxy where the statistical route is provably hard.

\paragraph{The injected-vs-learned inversion and the Director caveat.}
The only hierarchy arm that buys competence has \emph{injected}, hand-defined skill
structure (\S\ref{sec:results-hier}); the learned/generative NULL
(Table~\ref{tab:bet2null}) \emph{inverts} LeCun's Bet~2,
which is specifically about \emph{learned} hierarchical abstraction. We are careful
not to over-claim: Director~\citep{hafner2022director} shows generative latent world
models already do competitive hierarchical latent planning, so LeCun's generativity
sub-claim is not adjudicated --- our running generative reference (DreamerV3) is
single-level, conflating generativity with depth. We therefore frame our result as
\emph{testing} the bet; a generative \emph{2-level} (Director-style) baseline
(\S\ref{sec:results-hier}) is required before any claim that a non-generative
abstract latent, or that injected over learned structure, is necessary.

\paragraph{Limits.}
(i) The behavioral-abstraction taxonomy (\S\ref{sec:taxonomy}) has
\emph{one task per cell} that is naturally hard for escape (Pendulum); the escape
cell is otherwise carried by the \emph{controlled} cartpole actuation frontier
rather than by multiple naturally-hard tasks, and is budget-bounded (escape is
capacity-in-practice, not a proof of differing asymptotes).
(ii) The hierarchy test uses a bounded 2-level subgoal/skill hierarchy on existing
infrastructure as the \emph{minimal decisive test}; a true differentiable
multi-level H-JEPA with subgoal emission is a multi-week effort and remains future
work. The learned/generative cells of Table~\ref{tab:bet2null} are verified flat
$0.0$, but on H-JEPA seed~0 only (corroborated across three HL architectures); a
generative \emph{2-level} arm remains the cleanest unrun disentanglement.
(iii) DreamerV3 is a \emph{single-level} generative reference, so it conflates
generativity with single-level rather than isolating generativity at fixed depth.
(iv) The escape frontier and behavioral tables are reported as deterministic
$n=64$ / multi-seed where stated; the hierarchy peak-success numbers are
training-eval peaks with deterministic re-scores where noted --- we flag this
training-eval vs.\ deterministic distinction per table rather than blurring it.
(v) Long-horizon manipulation has physical/kinematic ceilings (the ${\sim}0.83$
PickCube ceiling is physical), so we measure speed to a reachable threshold, not
the ceiling. (vi) The entity-graph OOD result and several graph-side measurements
are single-seed / synthetic with documented caveats. (vii) The crowded 2026
JEPA-derivative space requires a fresh related-work sweep at submission.
\todo{run the submission-time related-work sweep over 2602/2603 arXiv stems; do not
cite post-cutoff derivatives without verification.}

% =====================================================================
\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

We reframed a decade of inconsistent ``does abstraction help?'' results as an
axis mismatch: the field scores asymptotic return, whereas LeCun's world-model
program and Chollet's measure of intelligence both argue the right axis is speed
of learning. Decomposing LeCun's program into a metric bet and an architecture
bet, we tested both under one matched-control, speed-of-learning protocol. The
metric bet is confirmed: representational, behavioral, and temporal abstraction
are null on asymptote and real only on sample-efficiency --- and we organize the
behavioral findings on a two-axis taxonomy whose escape cell we turn into a
controlled actuation frontier, where a structured prior shifts the \emph{solvable}
boundary that a budget-matched baseline cannot cross. The architecture bet is, on
the verified evidence, a \emph{qualified, injected-only} GO: hierarchy depth and
subgoal horizon are genuine speed levers, the ${\sim}0.2$ plateau is a task
ceiling rather than a method limit, yet no hierarchical arm lifts the asymptote and
the depth advantage dissolves at $2\times$ budget. The only hierarchy that helps is
the one whose structure is \emph{injected}: every \emph{learned/generative} arm
LeCun bets on (DreamerV3, three H-JEPA variants) sits flat at $0.0$
(Table~\ref{tab:bet2null}), a verified NULL whose mechanism is the unlearnable
sub-centimeter reach primitive. Every abstraction lever we tested buys speed (or
budget-bounded escape), not asymptotic capacity. The one decisive remaining test
--- a Director-style generative-\emph{2-level} baseline that isolates generativity
at fixed hierarchy depth --- is pending.

